FeatNavigator: Automatic Feature Augmentation on Tabular Data

Jiaming Liang1âˆ—, Chuan Lei2, Xiao Qin2, Jiani Zhang2,
Asterios Katsifodimos2,3, Christos Faloutsos2,4, Huzefa Rangwala2 1University of Pennsylvania, 2AWS AI Research & Education, 3TU Delft, 4Carnegie Mellon University

Abstract.

Data-centric AI focuses on understanding and utilizing high-quality, relevant data in training machine learning (ML) models, thereby increasing the likelihood of producing accurate and useful results. Automatic feature augmentation, aiming to augment the initial base table with useful features from other tables, is critical in data preparation as it improves model performance, robustness, and generalizability. While recent works have investigated automatic feature augmentation, most of them have limited capabilities in utilizing all useful features as many of them are in candidate tables not directly joinable with the base table. Worse yet, with numerous join paths leading to these distant features, existing solutions fail to fully exploit them within a reasonable compute budget.

We present FeatNavigator, an effective and efficient framework that explores and integrates high-quality features in relational tables for ML models. FeatNavigator evaluates a feature from two aspects: (1) the intrinsic value of a feature towards an ML task (i.e., feature importance) and (2) the efficacy of a join path connecting the feature to the base table (i.e., integration quality). FeatNavigator strategically selects a small set of available features and their corresponding join paths to train a feature importance estimation model and an integration quality prediction model. Furthermore, FeatNavigatorâ€™s search algorithm exploits both estimated feature importance and integration quality to identify the optimized feature augmentation plan. Our experimental results show that FeatNavigator outperforms state-of-the-art solutions on five public datasets by up to 40.1% in ML model performance.

1. Introduction

Feature augmentation is a crucial process that enhances machine learning (ML) model performanceÂ (Kanter and Veeramachaneni, 2015; Chepurko etÂ al., 2020; Liu etÂ al., 2022; Galhotra etÂ al., 2023). The process of feature augmentation on tabular data typically involves feature exploration and integration. Feature exploration identifies useful features among candidate tables that could reveal additional insights or patterns. And feature integration decides how to join the selected candidate tables with the base table to augment the initial training data. Open tabular data repositories such as Google Dataset Search111https://datasetsearch.research.google.com/, Kaggle222https://www.kaggle.com/datasets, and OpenML333https://www.openml.org/ provide diverse tabular data that capture a wide range of features. By exploring and integrating features from these repositories of data, ML models can generalize to more patternsÂ (Chen etÂ al., 2020), overcome overfittingÂ (Ying, 2019), thereby leading to improved performance on unseen dataÂ (Chepurko etÂ al., 2020; Liu etÂ al., 2022; Galhotra etÂ al., 2023).

Motivating Example. FigureÂ 1 shows an example of feature augmentation on a toy dataset with a classification task. The base table is product, in which recommend is the target column, indicating whether the product should be recommended or not. The tables category, rating, review, and order are directly joinable with product. And collection, dispute and customer are candidate tables indirectly joinable with product through the other tables. Assuming that the features (e.g., address) from customer are useful to the prediction task, three join paths can be used to augment the base table product. However, these paths are not equivalent as customers may not provide ratings or reviews for all purchased products. In fact, the join path, customer â‹ˆâ‹ˆ\bowtie order â‹ˆâ‹ˆ\bowtie product (indicated by the thick red line), provides the highest quality to augment the base table. One can only discover that by actually joining these tables, which can be expensive when involving multiple large tables. When the prior knowledge about feature importance is missing, it becomes more challenging to examine all candidate tables, including both directly and indirectly joinable ones. Expensive joins need to be executed in order to find out the actual benefit of an augmented table to the prediction task. Worse yet, certain joins (e.g., product â‹ˆâ‹ˆ\bowtie category and product â‹ˆâ‹ˆ\bowtie rating indicated by the thick orange lines) are repeated multiple times when exploring different tables.

State-of-the-art Approaches. Early worksÂ (Kumar etÂ al., 2016; Chepurko etÂ al., 2020) augment the base table by joining other tables based on either their relevancy to the base table or the improvement of the contained features bring to the ML models. However, they assume that the features and their respective relevance to the base table are specified. Hence they fail to leverage all possible candidate feature and consequently do not reach the optimal model performance. Recently, ALITEÂ (Khatiwada etÂ al., 2022) and DIALITEÂ (Khatiwada etÂ al., 2023b) are introduced to integrate tables based on joinability or unionability, which can improve the quality of downstream applications (e.g., ML models).

Reinforcement learning (RL)Â (Vermorel and Mohri, 2005; Wang etÂ al., 2016) has emerged as an effective approach to balance between feature exploration and exploitation. Several studiesÂ (Liu etÂ al., 2022; Chai etÂ al., 2022; Galhotra etÂ al., 2023) leverage RL techniques, such as multi-armed bandits and Deep Q Networks (DQNs), to explore the large search space of candidate tables. Although these RL-based methods have achieved promising results, they still face critical challenges. Specifically, METAMÂ (Galhotra etÂ al., 2023) is limited to direct joinable candidate tables and AutoFeatureÂ (Liu etÂ al., 2022) does not provide fine-grained optimization on integration quality. Moreover, RL often relies on a large number of samples to learn effectively (DQNs in particular), and tends to overfit to the training environment, leading to poor performance in slightly different real-world situations.

Challenges. Based on the above observations, we aim to address the following open challenges.

  1. (1)

    Integration Quality. In real-world open data settings, a candidate table can be integrated with the base table via multiple join paths, which often have very different integration quality. Hence, it is critical to identify the optimal join path to achieve the full potential (i.e., feature importance) of a candidate table.

  2. (2)

    Expensive Join Operations. Join operations are computationally expensive and time consuming, especially when a long join path involves multiple joins. Candidate tables from open data repositories often share similar join paths. Therefore, avoiding or sharing join operations is imperative to efficient feature augmentation.

  3. (3)

    Search Complexity. The search space of all candidate tables along with all integration paths is intractable, making it prohibitively expensive to find the optimal set of candidate tables. To address this challenge, we need effective strategies to reduce the search space without compromising optimality.

Proposed Solution. To cope with the above mentioned challenges, we propose FeatNavigator, an efficient and effective framework for automatic feature augmentation. Given a base table, a set of candidate tables and a ML task, FeatNavigator first effectively selects a subset of candidate tables using a lightweight clustering algorithm based on table characteristics (e.g., embeddings, statistics, semantics, etc.). FeatNavigator further chooses representative join paths from these candidate tables to the base table. This allows FeatNavigator to not only find out the actual performance gain led by the candidate tables following the join paths but also learn an integration quality model and a feature importance estimator to calculate the performance gain of any unexplored candidate tables and their respective join paths. Lastly, FeatNavigatorâ€™s path search algorithm utilizes the integration quality model and feature importance estimator to further prune the search space and finds the optimized integration paths for the selected candidate tables in polynomial time. In case of having new tables added or table updates to the data repository, FeatNavigatorâ€™s integration quality model and feature importance estimator can effectively and efficiently estimate the performance gain without retraining. In polynomial time, FeatNavigatorâ€™s search algorithm produces new optimized integration paths if the estimated performance gain is higher than the one of the existing paths.

Contributions. Our main contributions are the following.

  1. (1)

    We introduce FeatNavigator, a novel feature augmentation framework designed for ML tasks over tabular data repositories.

  2. (2)

    We decompose the intractable problem of feature augmentation into two sub-problems, feature importance and integration quality, and consequently prove the relationship between them.

  3. (3)

    We design an effective feature exploration module consisting of a lightweight clustering-based feature importance estimation and an effective LSTM-based integration quality model.

  4. (4)

    We propose an efficient feature path search algorithm that exploits both estimated feature importance and integration quality to identify high-quality features and their optimized join paths for integration.

  5. (5)

    Our experiments show that FeatNavigator outperforms state-of-the-art baselines on different ML tasks over five public datasets with up to 40.1% improvement ML model performance.

Problem Statement. Given a base table Tbâ€‹aâ€‹sâ€‹esubscriptğ‘‡ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘ ğ‘’T_{base}, a set of candidate tables ğ’¯ğ’¯\mathcal{T}, and a ML task, our goal is to select a subset of tables from ğ’¯ğ’¯\mathcal{T} and to identify the best join paths to augment with Tbâ€‹aâ€‹sâ€‹esubscriptğ‘‡ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘ ğ‘’T_{base}, such that the utility gain Uâ€‹Gğ‘ˆğºUG of the ML task on Taâ€‹uâ€‹gsubscriptğ‘‡ğ‘ğ‘¢ğ‘”T_{aug} is maximized.

The complexity of choosing a subset of tables (i.e., feature selection) generally increases exponentially with the number of candidate tables (features), as all possible combinations of features need to be evaluated, making the problem NP-hard. Even with various heuristic and optimization techniquesÂ (John etÂ al., 1994; Battiti, 1994) to reduce the complexity, the cost of feature selection can be still expensive. Worse yet, enumerating all possible join paths among the base and candidate tables is prohibitively expensive due to its exponential time complexity in the worst case. The combination of these two exponential search spaces makes the problem intractable, consequently needing an effective and efficient method.

2.2. FeatNavigatorÂ System Overview

For a given ML task, FeatNavigator takes input as a base table with a prediction task on the target column and a tabular data repository consisting of candidate tables with features. FeatNavigator leverages data discovery systems such as AurumÂ (Fernandez etÂ al., 2018) or NYU AuctusÂ (Castelo etÂ al., 2021) to identify the candidate tables within kğ‘˜k-hop joins to the base tables. FeatNavigatorÂ then triggers its utility gain model in two stages.

In the exploration stage, FeatNavigator takes the following four steps. (1) It first groups the identified features into clusters based on their representations (embeddings, data distributions, types, etc.) using an efficient clustering algorithm. (2) To train the integration quality model, FeatNavigator employs a path selection strategy to choose a number of features and candidate join paths. (3) FeatNavigator then follows the selected join paths to integrate the target features into the base table and runs AutoML (e.g., AutoGluon555https://auto.gluon.ai/) to find out the actual utility gain compared to the model performance only using the base table. (4) FeatNavigator effectively collects a sufficient amount of training data to train the integration quality model and also assigns the actual feature importance to the selected features in the clusters. The importance of the other features can be estimated based on their relative distance to the ones with the actual importance assigned.

In the exploitation stage, FeatNavigator leverages both a feature importance estimator and an integration quality model to conduct an efficient and effective search over all identified features and their associated join paths. It iteratively selects the most important feature and uses the integration quality model to select the optimal join path (i.e., best integration quality) until a predefined number of features is reached. FeatNavigator then follows the selected join paths to integrate the selected features with the base table and generates the final augmented table for the given ML task. Finally, AutoML solutions (e.g., AutoGluon) can train, select and deploy the best performing machine learning model on the augmented tableÂ (Erickson etÂ al., 2020).

3. Utility Gain Modeling

As discussed in SectionÂ 2.1, the problem of maximizing utility gain for a given ML task is intractable. Hence we propose to decompose this problem into two sub-problems, namely maximizing feature importance and maximizing integration quality. The motivation behind this decomposition is that the effectiveness of a candidate feature relies on two critical factors, namely (1) feature importance â€“ how useful is a feature to the ML model if it can be fully leveraged (e.g., the significance of product ratings in the context of product recommendations), and (2) integration quality â€“ how many data instances in the base table can be augmented by a feature from a candidate table. In the rest of this section, we will introduce several key concepts to help define these two factors and use them together to derive the decomposition and our final optimization goal. The detailed algorithms for achieving the derived optimization goal are then introduced in the next section.

The virtual table Tvâ€‹iâ€‹râ€‹tsubscriptğ‘‡ğ‘£ğ‘–ğ‘Ÿğ‘¡T_{virt} refers to the ideal case where there exists a join path Pğ‘ƒP such that every instance in Tbâ€‹aâ€‹sâ€‹esubscriptğ‘‡ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘ ğ‘’T_{base} can be augmented by a feature instance from Tcsubscriptğ‘‡ğ‘T_{c} via this Pğ‘ƒP (i.e., iPhone 15 with a rating of 5, Pixel 8 with a rating of 4.5, and Galaxy S23 with a rating of 4 shown in FigureÂ 3(b)). Note that a virtual table is specific to a base table and an individual candidate feature.

4. Integration Quality & Feature Importance Estimation

The utility gain has been shown to have a linear relationship with integration quality (Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ) and feature importance (Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI) in TheoremÂ 3.6. However, both Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ and Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI are computational expensive to obtain as they require resource intensive joins and model training, particularly when dealing with a large number of features and their associated join paths. As a result, estimating Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ and Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI to avoid costly joins and model training becomes imperative. In this section, we delves into our proposed solution for Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ and Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI estimation as well as data selection strategy for estimation model training.

4.1. Integration Quality Estimation

4.2. Feature Importance Estimation

Feature importance estimation has been studiedÂ (Lundberg and Lee, 2017; Hooker etÂ al., 2018; Å krlj etÂ al., 2020) in recent years. However, these methods are often computationally expensive and model specific. Hence we introduce a simple and effective clustering-based method to estimate the feature importance. The intuition is that features with similar representations in the embedding space tend to have a similar impact (i.e., feature importance) on the ML taskÂ (Lundberg and Lee, 2017; Galhotra etÂ al., 2023). The clustering algorithm exploits this observation to compute the representative featuresâ€™ Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI in each cluster and estimate Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI of other features based on their proximity to the representative ones, which leads to substantial computational savings. In the following, we explain four steps to estimate feature importance in detail.

Feature Representation. The representation of a feature column ci,jsubscriptğ‘ğ‘–ğ‘—c_{i,j} consists of two parts: (1) column metadata, and (2) column data instances. We use a pre-trained language model (PLM) such as BERTÂ (Devlin etÂ al., 2018) to generate the embeddings of column metadata such as column names, column semantic types, column description, if available. For data instances in a feature column, we sample the column, serialize the sample data, and use a PLM to generate the embeddings as well. Finally, we concatenate the embeddings of both column metadata and data instances as the feature representation.

Feature Clustering. We design the clustering method based on DBSCANÂ (Ester etÂ al., 1996). To be specific, we first randomly select an unexplored feature and check the number of features that lie within its Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilon-neighborhood, where Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilon denotes the threshold of cosine similarity between two feature representations. Then we check if the Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilon-neighborhood of this selected feature contains at least mğ‘šm features. If so we form a cluster by adding all unexplored features within the selected featureâ€™s Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilon-neighborhood. We iterate this process until all features have been assigned to a cluster. Unlike DBSCAN, we do not consider any feature as noise. Namely, the remaining unexplored features will be considered as clusters of their own. The advantage of this lightweight method is that it bounds the similarity between the centroid feature and other candidate features within a cluster, i.e., câ€‹oâ€‹sâ€‹(Râ€‹eâ€‹pâ€‹râ€‹(câ€‹eâ€‹nâ€‹tâ€‹râ€‹oâ€‹iâ€‹d),Râ€‹eâ€‹pâ€‹râ€‹(câ€‹aâ€‹nâ€‹dâ€‹iâ€‹dâ€‹aâ€‹tâ€‹ei))â‰¤Ïµğ‘ğ‘œğ‘ ğ‘…ğ‘’ğ‘ğ‘Ÿğ‘ğ‘’ğ‘›ğ‘¡ğ‘Ÿğ‘œğ‘–ğ‘‘ğ‘…ğ‘’ğ‘ğ‘Ÿğ‘ğ‘ğ‘›ğ‘‘ğ‘–ğ‘‘ğ‘ğ‘¡subscriptğ‘’ğ‘–italic-Ïµcos(Repr(centroid),Repr(candidate_{i}))\leq\epsilon.

Compute Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI. According to DefinitionÂ 3.1, we need to follow one or more join paths to integrate a feature to the base table in order to compute its Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI. Naively, one could utilize all join paths between the base table and the feature table to obtain its maximum Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI, which is very costly. In SectionÂ 4.3, we will introduce a data selection strategy that chooses features and their associated join paths for both Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI computation and LSTM network training.

Estimate Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI for Unseen Features. For a unseen feature, we estimate its Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI by a weighted average over the Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI of its surrounding features in the same feature cluster. Precisely, we have

where cğ‘c denotes the unseen feature, Nğ‘N denotes the set of features with known Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI in the same cluster, and câ€‹oâ€‹sâ€‹(â‹…)ğ‘ğ‘œğ‘ â‹…cos(\cdot) represents the cosine similarity between the unseen feature and its neighboring feature. For example, FigureÂ 6 illustrates f1,2subscriptğ‘“12f_{1,2}â€™s Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilon-neighborhood. 4.3. Data Selection for Estimation

Now we introduce an effective data selection strategy for Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ model training and Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI estimation, both of which require expensive join executions according to the chosen join paths. In addition, Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI needs to feed the augmented table to an AutoML framework (e.g., AutoGluon) to obtain the actual feature importance. Hence our goal is to choose high quality data points to serve both Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ and Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI estimations, in the form of feature-path (fi,jsubscriptğ‘“ğ‘–ğ‘—f_{i,j}, Pksubscriptğ‘ƒğ‘˜P_{k}) pairs. Ideally, the selected data points should have two desired properties. First, the selected integration paths should have a good coverage over all joins among any candidate tables and the base table. The covered joins can be stitched together to accurately estimate unexplored integration paths. Second, the selected features should be evenly distributed across all feature clusters. The number of features chosen from one cluster should be proportioned to the size of the cluster.

To achieve two properties above, we consider the following factors regarding a feature-path pair and propose a weight function to rank all feature-path pairs.

  1. (1)

    Single join path coverage (Pâ€‹Cğ‘ƒğ¶PC) represents how much a join path has been explored. This is measured by the ratio between the number of join edges in a join path that have been explored and the total number of join edges in the path.

  2. (2)

    lğ‘™l-hop join path group coverage (Pâ€‹Gâ€‹Cğ‘ƒğºğ¶PGC) represents the number of join paths of a length lğ‘™l that have been fully explored. This is measured by the ratio between the number of fully explored lğ‘™l-hop join paths and the total number of lğ‘™l-hop paths.

  3. (3)

    Feature cluster coverage (Fâ€‹Cğ¹ğ¶FC) represents the number of features that have been examined in a feature cluster. This is measured by the ratio between the number of tested features and the total number of features in a cluster.

Note that all the above factors range between [0, 1] and a lower value of each factor indicates that a path or a feature should be explored. Hence the weight function is defined as

(8) wâ€‹(fi,j,Pk)=Pâ€‹CÃ—Pâ€‹Gâ€‹CÃ—Fâ€‹C.ğ‘¤subscriptğ‘“ğ‘–ğ‘—subscriptğ‘ƒğ‘˜ğ‘ƒğ¶ğ‘ƒğºğ¶ğ¹ğ¶w(f_{i,j},P_{k})=PC\times PGC\times FC.

We assign a score to each feature-path pair using this weight function, rank them in an ascending order to select the one with the smallest weight in each iteration. After each iteration, we update the weights, re-rank the feature-path pairs and continue the selection until a given budget is exhausted. AlgorithmÂ 1 details the greedy data point selection method.

AlgorithmÂ 1 first initializes several data structures including the ones to store the intermediate states of single join path coverage, lğ‘™l-hop join path group coverage, feature cluster coverage, and the weights for all unselected feature-path pairs (Lines 1-7). Then the feature-path pair with the smallest weight is chosen and removed from the set of unselected pairs (Lines 9-11). Note that we randomly select one feature-path pair if there are multiple ones with the smallest weight. Once a feature-path pair is chosen, the join path coverage, join path group coverage, and feature cluster coverage are updated accordingly (Lines 12-17). The weights of the remaining unselected pairs are recomputed based on EquationÂ 8 (Lines 18-20). We iterate this process until the given budget is exhausted or all feature-path pairs are selected.

5. Feature Search and Integration

In this section, we present FeatNavigatorâ€™s search algorithm that efficiently and effectively exploits the integration quality and feature importance estimations to identify an augmentation plan that maximizes the utility gain of a ML task.

5.1. Join Graph Model

We first introduce FeatNavigator join graph model to capture the search space of all integration plans.

Definition 5.1 (FeatNavigator Join Graph).

A FeatNavigator join graph ğ’¢=(V,E)ğ’¢ğ‘‰ğ¸\mathcal{G}=(V,E) is a unweighted and undirected graph with a set of vertices and a set of edges. A vertex vâˆˆVğ‘£ğ‘‰v\in V represents a table, consisting of a set of features F={f1,â€¦,fn}ğ¹subscriptğ‘“1â€¦subscriptğ‘“ğ‘›F=\{f_{1},...,f_{n}\}, and an edge eâˆˆEğ‘’ğ¸e\in E represents a join between two tables.

Given a join graph ğ’¢ğ’¢\mathcal{G}, a source vertex vbsubscriptğ‘£ğ‘v_{b} (i.e., the base table), and a given budget BğµB, the goal is to identify no more than BğµB features and their respective integration paths in ğ’¢ğ’¢\mathcal{G} to maximize the utility score of the ML task. Note that each path starts from vbsubscriptğ‘£ğ‘v_{b} and ends with a feature fi,jsubscriptğ‘“ğ‘–ğ‘—f_{i,j} associated with a vertex visubscriptğ‘£ğ‘–v_{i}.

Naively, we can follow the breadth-first search (BFS) approach to enumerate all integration paths from vbsubscriptğ‘£ğ‘v_{b}. For a path Pjsubscriptğ‘ƒğ‘—P_{j} leading to visubscriptğ‘£ğ‘–v_{i}, we form feature-path pairs for all features in visubscriptğ‘£ğ‘–v_{i}. Among all feature-path pairs, we generate all possible candidate combinations with â‰¤Babsentğµ\leq B features. The utility score of each candidate combination is computed based on the Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ and Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI estimation. The combination with the maximum utility score represents the optimal solution to the feature augmentation problem. While this naive solution guarantees an optimal solution, it suffers from the combinatorial explosion problem. Specifically, real-world datasets often consist of many candidate tables and join relationships, resulting in a dense join graph. For instance, the School dataset from our experiments has over 10,000 join paths. Worse yet, with nğ‘›n candidate features, a budget of at most selecting BğµB of them, and on average mğ‘šm integration paths for each feature, the number of combinations is âˆ‘i=1Bmâ‹…(ni)superscriptsubscriptğ‘–1ğµâ‹…ğ‘šbinomialğ‘›ğ‘–\sum_{i=1}^{B}m\cdot\binom{n}{i} (e.g., the School dataset has more than 108superscript10810^{8} combinations).

5.2. Search and Refinement

We introduce two pruning principles below to progressively reduce the search space, preventing the search explosion in the early stage without sacrificing the quality of feature augmentation.

Pruning Principle 1 (Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ Monotonicity). Based on DefinitionÂ 3.2, the integration quality monotonically decreases as a path extends. In other words, if the Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ of a path Pğ‘ƒP is too low, it is not beneficial to explore any path that has Pğ‘ƒP as its prefix. This fundamental principle is critical for path exploration with early termination.

Pruning Principle 2 (Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI Lower Bound). If the feature importance of a feature fisubscriptğ‘“ğ‘–f_{i} is too low, then fisubscriptğ‘“ğ‘–f_{i} and all integration paths to fisubscriptğ‘“ğ‘–f_{i} can be safely pruned. The rationale behind this principle is based on TheoremÂ 3.6. Specifically, if fisubscriptğ‘“ğ‘–f_{i}â€™s Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI is too low, its Uâ€‹Gğ‘ˆğºUG would still be negligible even there were a perfect integration path (i.e., Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ = 1). Note that the lower bound of Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI can be progressively increased as we explore the search space and identify more useful features.

Search with Progressive Pruning. Leveraging these two pruning principles, we introduce FeatNavigatorâ€™s search algorithm (AlgorithmÂ 2) for feature selection and their corresponding join path exploration. AlgorithmÂ 2 employs a BFS-based approach to identify feature candidates and their integration paths iteratively. It starts with the base table (Line 2) and iteratively extends its search to kğ‘˜k-hop features (Lines 4-25).

During this process, we maintain a min-heap of size Hğ»H that keeps top-Hğ»H candidate feature-path pairs câ€‹aâ€‹nâ€‹dâ€‹iâ€‹dâ€‹aâ€‹tâ€‹eâ€‹sğ‘ğ‘ğ‘›ğ‘‘ğ‘–ğ‘‘ğ‘ğ‘¡ğ‘’ğ‘ candidates, sorted by the Uâ€‹Gğ‘ˆğºUG score in a descending order (Line 3). Note that the heap size Hğ»H is larger than the feature budget BğµB so as to maintain a superset of candidates for further refinement. In practice, we set Hğ»H to a multiple of BğµB. We then iterate through each kğ‘˜k-hop path in Pcâ€‹uâ€‹rsubscriptğ‘ƒğ‘ğ‘¢ğ‘ŸP_{cur} (line 6), extending the path to include an additional vertex vğ‘£v directly connected to the last vertex uğ‘¢u of the path (Lines 6-12). Subsequently, we compute the Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ for the extended path (pâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²p^{\prime}) and discard it if its Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ is below TIâ€‹Qsubscriptğ‘‡ğ¼ğ‘„T_{IQ} (Lines 13-14). For the qualified pâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²p^{\prime}, we add it to the set of (k+1)ğ‘˜1(k+1)-hop paths Pnâ€‹eâ€‹xâ€‹tsubscriptğ‘ƒğ‘›ğ‘’ğ‘¥ğ‘¡P_{next}, and evaluate the Uâ€‹Gğ‘ˆğºUG for each feature on vertex vğ‘£v. The feature-path pair with the lowest Uâ€‹Gğ‘ˆğºUG score in câ€‹aâ€‹nâ€‹dâ€‹iâ€‹dâ€‹aâ€‹tâ€‹eâ€‹sğ‘ğ‘ğ‘›ğ‘‘ğ‘–ğ‘‘ğ‘ğ‘¡ğ‘’ğ‘ candidates is used as the lower bound. We update câ€‹aâ€‹nâ€‹dâ€‹iâ€‹dâ€‹aâ€‹tâ€‹eâ€‹sğ‘ğ‘ğ‘›ğ‘‘ğ‘–ğ‘‘ğ‘ğ‘¡ğ‘’ğ‘ candidates with the qualified feature-path pair (Lines 16-18). Finally, the algorithm returns the candidate set (Line 26).

Feature Augmentation Refinement. Among the selected feature-path candidates, similar features in the same cluster are expected to have comparable effect on the downstream ML taskÂ (Galhotra etÂ al., 2023). In light of this observation, we design a weight decay method to refine the selected feature candidates and to produce the final feature augmentation plan. In essence, this weight decay method aims to mitigate the local optimum incurred by choosing similar features during the search process.

Specifically, the weight decay method relies on a scaling factor using feature similarity to regulate the Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI on related features, subsequently optimizing the overall efficacy of selected features in the downstream tasks. The weight decay function on a feature fğ‘“f is

where Nğ‘N represents the set of already chosen features in the same cluster. The closer a feature to the other chosen features in the same cluster, the more penalty it receives. In the refinement process, we iteratively choose the feature-path pair with the maximum Uâ€‹Gğ‘ˆğºUG and update the Uâ€‹Gğ‘ˆğºUG of the remaining pairs based on the equation above. After BğµB iterations, we select top-BğµB feature-path pairs as the feature augmentation plan.

AlgorithmÂ 3 illustrates the refinement strategy in detail. It first initializes the estimated Uâ€‹Gğ‘ˆğºUG based on Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ and Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI of each candidate feature-path pair (Lines 2-4). During each iteration, it performs two key steps: (1) among unselected feature-path pairs, it selects the feature and corresponding path with the highest estimated Uâ€‹Gğ‘ˆğºUG (Line 9); and (2) it updates the estimated Uâ€‹Gğ‘ˆğºUG for remaining feature-path pairs based on the above equation (Line 13). This adjustment indicates that a higher similarity between a unselected feature and the already chosen ones leads to a lower Uâ€‹Gğ‘ˆğºUG value for the unselected feature, implying a reduced contribution to the ML task. Finally, the selected feature-path pairs sâ€‹eâ€‹lâ€‹eâ€‹câ€‹tâ€‹eâ€‹dğ‘ ğ‘’ğ‘™ğ‘’ğ‘ğ‘¡ğ‘’ğ‘‘selected are returned after a given feature budget BğµB is exhausted (Line 16).

6. Experimental Evaluation

6.1. Experimental Setup

Datasets. We evaluate FeatNavigator over five public datasets by performing classification and regression tasks. All five datasets are composed of base tables provided by Kaggle and the DARPA Data Driven Discovery of Models (D3M)777https://datadrivendiscovery.org/about-d3m/. Given a base table, we searched open source datasets for joinable tables using NYU AuctusÂ (Castelo etÂ al., 2021) to identify candidate tables for augmentation purpose.

  • â€¢

    School is a dataset commonly used in baselinesÂ (Chepurko etÂ al., 2020; Liu etÂ al., 2022; Galhotra etÂ al., 2023) for a classification task. The target prediction is school performance on a standardized test based on student attributes, course attributes and other historical surveys.

  • â€¢

    DonorsChoose888https://www.kaggle.com/c/donorschoose-application-screening is a Kaggle dataset for a classification task. The target prediction is whether or not a DonorsChoose proposal was accepted. We identified 122 candidate features for augmentation.

  • â€¢

    Fraud Detection999https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/ieee-fraud-detection is a Kaggle dataset consisting of over 800 candidate features. The task is to predict whether an online transaction is fraudulent.

  • â€¢

    Poverty consists of socioeconomic features like poverty rates, population change, unemployment rates, and education levels across U.S. States and counties. The task is to predict an index indicating poverty level.

  • â€¢

    Air is a regression dataset from NYU Auctus and google aiming to predict the air quality of a city on a given date.

Note that tables from Kaggle are typically wide, consisting of many features already integrated with base tables. Hence we normalize these wide tables and consequently generate candidate tables with features more than 1-hop away from the original base tables. TableÂ 1 provides the basic information about the three datasets and the numbers of immediate (1-hop) and distant features.

Baselines. We compared FeatNavigator with a variety of baselines, including heuristic-based solutions such as Deep Feature Synthesis and ARDA as well as machine learning-based solutions such as AutoFeature and METAM.

  • â€¢

    Deep Feature Synthesis (DFS)Â (Kanter and Veeramachaneni, 2015) is a pioneer work that automatically generates features for relational datasets. It utilizes join paths in the data to a base table, and then applies mathematical functions along these paths to create the final features.

  • â€¢

    ARDAÂ (Chepurko etÂ al., 2020) is a feature augmentation system, which employs a variety of heuristics to select top-kğ‘˜k tables to join and uses a random injection-based feature augmentation to search candidate feature subsets.

  • â€¢

    AutoFeatureÂ (Liu etÂ al., 2022) is a reinforcement learning based framework to augment the features following an exploration-exploitation strategy over the search space of candidate tables (features).

  • â€¢

    METAMÂ (Galhotra etÂ al., 2023) is a goal-oriented framework that queries the downstream task with a candidate dataset, using a feedback loop that automatically steers the discovery and augmentation process.

6.2. Baseline Comparison

We first conduct an end-to-end evaluation of FeatNavigator against the state-of-the-art solutions for feature augmentation. In this set of experiments, we study the effectiveness of FeatNavigator on finding the most useful features from candidate tables within a given budget. The budge BğµB is defined as the number of features allowed to augment the base table. We vary the budget from 1, 5 to 10 and report the utility measurements of different methods on the datasets. As shown in TableÂ 2, when B>ğµabsentB> 1, FeatNavigator consistently demonstrates superior performance on finding and integrating features that contribute the most to the task on the base table. The reason is that FeatNavigator not only accurately identifies useful features that are different hops away but also exploits these features with high-quality integration paths.

When the budget is extremely limited (i.e., BğµB = 1), FeatNavigator is still among the top 2 performing methods. In both DonorChoose and Air datasets, the most useful feature is from an 1-hop candidate table, which also presents high joinability to the base table. And this information is given to ARDA and hence it is able to outperform FeatNavigator. METAM on the Fraud Detection dataset delivers the best performance by finding a 1-hop join path to the most useful feature. FeatNavigator is slightly worse than METAM due to its Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ and Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI estimation errors amplified by such an extreme budget.

6.3. Ablation Study

To better understand how our key designs of FeatNavigator benefit the overall performance feature augmentation, we conduct extensive ablation studies to evaluate the performance of FeatNavigatorâ€™s individual components and their variants.

6.3.1. Effectiveness of FeatNavigatorâ€™s Integration Quality Model.

First, we evaluate the accuracy of FeatNavigatorâ€™s LSTM-based Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ estimator. The ground truth is established by materializing the join paths and computing the corresponding Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ scores according to DefinitionÂ 3.2. We measure and report the MSE between the estimated values and the ground truth values. To make sense of the accuracy of the proposed Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ estimator, we compare it against two baselines: (1) multiplication of Transitivity scores between the tables on a join path (named Production), and (2) randomly predicting an Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ score between 0 and 1 (named Random [0,1]). In addition, we include an LSTM-based Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ estimator trained on randomly selected feature-path pairs and vary the number of training pairs.

Overall, FeatNavigatorâ€™s LSTM-based Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ estimator achieves the best (lowest) MSE compared to all baselines across three different datasets, as shown in FigureÂ 7. The random estimator performs the worst (highest) MSE. Notably, our method consistently outperforms both Production and Random methods, which empirically verifies the usefulness of the proposed features for our Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ estimator. With the increasing number (from 50 to 1000) of the training join paths |tâ€‹p|ğ‘¡ğ‘|tp|, our Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ estimator produces more accurate estimations. Note that 1000 training feature-path pairs only account for approximately 0.1% of all possible pairs in the smallest dataset (i.e., DonorsChoose). We also observe that random data selection strategy demonstrates competitive performance. It is expected as all test sets are randomly drawn from three datasets, respectively.

We further employ the saliency methodÂ (Simonyan etÂ al., 2014) to measure the importance of each input feature to the Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ model, by assessing their respective gradient concerning the predicted Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ value. As shown in FigureÂ 8, the Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ model benefits the most from Pearson correlation and variance, and the other features also contribute to the Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ to varying degrees with different datasets. This confirms that the chosen features are essential to a high-quality Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ estimator in FeatNavigator.

6.3.2. Effectiveness of FeatNavigatorâ€™s Feature Importance Estimator.

Second, we evaluate the accuracy of our Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI estimator. The ground truth is established by materializing the test join paths and computing the corresponding Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI scores using AutoGluon. We measure and report the MAE between the estimated values and the ground truth values. We also vary the size of the training set from 50 to 1000. To make sense of the MAE of our Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI estimator, we compare it against three alternative designs: (1) a random sampling method that randomly choose |f|ğ‘“|f| destination features for estimating Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI. We ensure that at least one sample is drawn from each cluster; (2) a top centroid-based method that allocate budgets uniformly across clusters. Within each cluster, we select the top central features; and (3) a top cover method that equally distributes budgets across clusters. The objective within each cluster is to identify points that minimize the coverage radius.

Overall, as shown in FigureÂ 9, we observe that FeatNavigatorâ€™s estimation quality (i.e., lower MAE) improves with an increasing number of data points collected from feature clusters. FeatNavigator outperforms the other baselines on School, Fraud Detection and Air datasets, and its performance on DonorsChoose and Poverty is also very close to the best performing top cover method. When the given budget is small (i.e., |f|â‰¤100)|f|\leq 100), the random sampling method is slightly more effective on DonorsChoose and School datasets. In fact, this is consistent with our observation in the above integration quality evaluation. Hence, one could take a hybrid approach that randomly samples the first 50 or 100 feature-path pairs and then adapts to the proposed data selection strategy when establishing the Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI estimator and the Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ model.

6.3.3. Effectiveness and Efficiency of FeatNavigatorâ€™s Search Algorithm.

Third, we evaluate the effectiveness and efficiency of FeatNavigatorâ€™s search algorithm. We report the final Accuracy or F1 as well as the compute time spent on search. To make sense of the measurements, we compare FeatNavigatorâ€™s search algorithm against two baselines: (1) an exhaustive method that uses BFS to exhaustively search and estimate all possible combinations of destination features and integration paths; and (2) a greedy method that chooses features with highest estimated Fâ€‹Iğ¹ğ¼FI for candidate features. For each candidate feature, it further selects the path with the fewest number of joins (i.e., shortest integration path). If more than one integration paths are the shortest, the greedy method picks the one with the highest estimated Iâ€‹Qğ¼ğ‘„IQ. In this experiment, we vary the feature budget from 1 to 10, to be consistent with TableÂ 2.

As shown in TableÂ 3, FeatNavigatorâ€™s search algorithm significantly outperforms the greedy algorithm and achieves similar performance to the exhaustive algorithm in Accuracy or F1. Regarding the efficiency, FeatNavigatorâ€™s search algorithm also achieves 2-5 times speedup compared to the exhaustive algorithm. Moreover, FeatNavigatorâ€™s compute time, on average, increases 2% when increasing the feature budget from 1 to 10. This shows that FeatNavigatorâ€™s search algorithm is scalable to a large number of features allowed for augmentation.

We further evaluate the performance of FeatNavigatorâ€™s search algorithm by varying heap sizes Hğ»H from 5 to 100 and report the final model performance and the search compute time. As shown in FigureÂ 10, the model performance shows solid improvements with an increasing heap size, while the latency only increases sub-linearly. This showcases that FeatNavigatorâ€™s search and refinement algorithms are effective and efficient.

6.4. End-to-End Latency

In TableÂ 4, we report the end-to-end latency of FeatNavigator and other baselines over three datasets. The feature budget is set to 10 to be consistent with TableÂ 2. Specifically, FeatNavigator is 2.1% and 18.4% faster than METAM on Fraud Detection and School datasets, and 6.2% faster than ARDA on DonorsChoose dataset. This shows that FeatNavigator not only delivers the best model performance but also has lower latency compared to the best performing baselines.

7. Related Work

Feature Augmentation. Automatic feature augmentation has been intensively studied and shown effective for various ML tasks including classification, regression, clustering, etc. Kumar et al.Â (Kumar etÂ al., 2016) focus on the problem of when to avoid primary key-foreign key join without sacrificing the performance of the model. Deep Feature Synthesis (DFS)Â (Kanter and Veeramachaneni, 2015) is one of the early work in generating features for relational datasets. DFS follows joinable relationships in the data to a base table, and then sequentially applies mathematical functions along that path to create the final features. ARDAÂ (Chepurko etÂ al., 2020) is a feature augmentation framework that leverages existing data discovery toolsÂ (Fernandez etÂ al., 2018) to score the candidate tables and uses a heuristic algorithm to select features. Hence, the performance of ARDA heavily relies on the scores given by Aurum, which are not always accurate as they are not model-aware.

Recently, AutoFeatureÂ (Liu etÂ al., 2022) leverages reinforcement learning (RL) for feature augmentation. It uses either a multi-armed bandits or a branch Deep Q Networks to choose between exploring features that could lead to performance improvement and exploiting features that are rarely selected. METAMÂ (Galhotra etÂ al., 2023) is a goal-oriented framework that also utilizes the multi-arm bandit method for feature discovery and augmentation to achieve the desired performance of a given task. It uses data properties, utility functions from downstream tasks and the given candidate dataset to drive the discovery and augmentation process. Coreset selectionÂ (Wang etÂ al., 2022; Chai etÂ al., 2023) aims to select a high-quality coreset without materializing the augmented table and uses weighted gradients of the selected coreset to approximate the full gradient of the entire train dataset.

Feature Selection. Feature selectionÂ (Chandrashekar and Sahin, 2014; Li etÂ al., 2017) aims to identify a subset of the most relevant features from a large dataset for a specific ML task, thereby reducing feature dimensionality. In contrast, feature augmentation involves increasing the number of features to enhance the modelâ€™s predictive capability. The ranking-based methods evaluate the importance of each feature using statistical metrics like correlation coefficient or mutual information with the labelsÂ (Guyon and Elisseeff, 2003) and then select the top relevant features. However, ranking-based methods may yield a sub-optimal subset with highly correlated variables, where a smaller subset would suffice.

Sequential selection and heuristic search algorithms optimize a utility gain objective function for feature subset evaluation. Due to the NP-hard nature of evaluating 2Nsuperscript2ğ‘2^{N} subsets, these methods find sub-optimal subsets heuristically. Sequential algorithmsÂ (Pudil etÂ al., 1994) either add or remove features from an initial empty (or full) set until the utility gain is maximized, using a criterion to incrementally enhance the utility gain with fewer features. Heuristic algorithmsÂ (Goldberg, 2013), on the other hand, explore different subsets, either by searching within a space or generating solutions to optimize the utility gain. More recently, Cherepanova et al.Â (Cherepanova etÂ al., 2023) propose an input-gradient-based analogue of Lasso for neural networks that outperforms classical feature selection methods on challenging problems such as selecting from corrupted or second-order features in the tabular deep learning setting. Liu et al.Â (Liu etÂ al., 2023) reformulate feature selection with a RL framework by regarding each feature as an agent.

Table Discovery. Table discovery systemsÂ (Fernandez etÂ al., 2018; Zhu etÂ al., 2019; Zhang and Ives, 2020; Dong etÂ al., 2023; Khatiwada etÂ al., 2023a; Hu etÂ al., 2023; Fan etÂ al., 2023) find joinable and unionable tables from data repositories to boost downstream applications, such as related table discovery, table QA, and ML models. Modern techniquesÂ (Zhang and Ives, 2020; Gong etÂ al., 2023) allow users to interactively search useful joinable datasets by specifying requirements in the form of data profiles or examples. However, without the information of ML models, it is difficult to identify which tables and join paths are useful to the downstream ML models.

8. Conclusion

In this paper, we propose a framework FeatNavigator for automatic feature augmentation. FeatNavigator tackles the intractable problem of feature augmentation by decomposing it into feature importance and integration quality. We design a lightweight clustering-based method for feature importance estimation and an LSTM-based integration quality model. We further introduce an efficient feature path search algorithm that exploits both estimated feature importance and integration quality to identify high-quality features and their optimized join paths for integration under a given budget. Our experiments on three public datasets demonstrate the effectiveness of FeatNavigator.
